'''James Campbell''', [[Fellow of the British Academy|FBA]] (26 January 1935 &ndash; 31 May 2016)<ref name="whoswho">{{cite book|title=CAMPBELL, James|year=2015|publisher=A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc; online edn. November 2015, Oxford University Press|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U10033|accessdate=1 June 2016}}</ref><ref name="WCnotice">{{cite web|title=Professor James Campbell passed away yesterday|url=http://www.worc.ox.ac.uk/about/news/professor-james-campbell-passed-away-yesterday|publisher=Worcester College, Oxford|accessdate=1 June 2016}}</ref> was a British [[historian]] with a particular interest in the Medieval period and [[Anglo-Saxon]] studies.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Interview with James Campbell |url=http://www.sms.cam.ac.uk/media/1382781 |publisher=University of Cambridge |location=Cambridge, England |accessdate=2 July 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ZifQDulL?url=http://www.sms.cam.ac.uk/media/1382781 |archivedate= 2 July 2015 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> Campbell was born in Cheltenham and was a [[fellow]] at [[Worcester College]], [[University of Oxford]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=James Campbell |url=http://www.worc.ox.ac.uk/about/fellows/james-campbell |publisher=University of Oxford |location=Oxford, England |accessdate=2 July 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ZifjLrjf?url=http://www.worc.ox.ac.uk/about/fellows/james-campbell |archivedate= 2 July 2015 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> where he served as the University's [[Proctor#Oxford University|Senior Proctor]] for 1973-74.<ref name="WCnotice" /> He was the editor of ''The Anglo-Saxons'' (1982), a collection of essays on [[Anglo-Saxon England]], for which he wrote the section on the period from 350 to 660 AD.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lrb.co.uk/v05/n21/john-gillingham/anglo-saxon-aptitudes|title=John Gillingham reviews ‘The Anglo-Saxons’ edited by James Campbell, ‘Anglo-Saxon Art’ by C.R. Dodwell, ‘Anglo-Saxon Poetry’ edited by S.A.J. Bradley, ‘The Anglo-Saxon World’ edited by Kevin Crossley-Holland and ‘The Anglo-Saxon Chronicles’ by Anne Savage|last=Gillingham|first=John|date=17 November 1983|work=[[London Review of Books]]|accessdate=20 July 2015}}</ref> He was elected as a Fellow of the [[British Academy]] in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|title=Directory of Fellows - C|url=http://www.britac.ac.uk/fellowship/directory/ord.cfm?letter=C|publisher=The British Academy|accessdate=1 June 2016|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041115/http://www.britac.ac.uk/fellowship/directory/ord.cfm?letter=C|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=}}</ref>
